  se:
    scheduler:
      schedules:
        populatejob	
          job-group: f.step
          job-name: populatejob
          job-class: <class path com.bac.populatejob>
          cron-trigger:
          cron-expression: 0 5 21 * * ?
          enabled: false
          description: populate 

The Scheduler (PopulateJob):
This is the "Trigger" for your data conversion.
Logic: It will execute the code in com.bac.populatejob every night at 9:05 PM (0 5 21 * * ?).
GitOps Role: Because enabled: false is set, the job is "dormant." In a GitOps workflow,
you would keep it disabled in your repository and only flip it to true via a Pull Request
when you are ready to start the migration or synchronization in a specific environment.

Field            Value / Meaning
job-class        populatejob — This is the Java class containing the logic to fetch data from MongoDB (StepV2) and prepare it for SQL.
cron-expression  0 5 21 * * ? — This job is scheduled to run every day at 9:05 PM.
enabled: false   Critical: The job is currently deactivated. It will not run automatically unless this is changed to true.
job-group        f.step — Used to categorize jobs in the Quartz monitor/database.

ferguson:
  se:
    caching:
          caches:
              class-by-id:	
                  valueClass: com.bac.DOClass
                  cache-provider: eh_cache

The Caching Configuration (Ehcache):
You are using Ehcache (a popular Java-based caching library) to store com.bac.DOClass objects in memory.
How it works:
When your application needs a DOClass object (likely a Data Object used during conversion), it follows this flow:
Check Cache: It looks in the class-by-id cache.
Cache Hit: If found, it returns the object immediately (Microseconds).
Cache Miss: If not found, it queries the Database (Mongo/SQL), populates the cache, and then returns the object (Milliseconds).

Why use "class-by-id" for Data Conversion?
In a Mongo-to-SQL migration, you often have Reference Data (like Product Categories or Tax Codes).
Instead of querying the database for the same Category 10,000 times during a bulk migration, Ehcache stores it in the JVM's memory.

@Service
public class ConversionService {
    @Cacheable(value = "class-by-id", key = "#id")
    public DOClass getReferenceData(String id) {
        // This only runs if the data is NOT in Ehcache
        return mongoRepository.findById(id);
    }
}

